  footnotes: []
english:
  title: On Clarifying the Heart
  author: Lee Cham
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Can the heart be clarified? Yes, it can. Is there a method? There is. Then let me ask: what is the method? The answer is this: the method lies in the absence of desire. Mencius said, "In nurturing the heart, nothing surpasses the reduction of desires. When a person has few desires, even if the heart wanders outward, such wandering is rare."

    Yet I believe that clarifying the heart goes beyond merely reducing desires and preserving what remains. For when desires are diminished, one approaches nothingness. When desire vanishes entirely, stillness and emptiness arise, and movement becomes upright. From stillness and emptiness come clarity and penetration. From upright movement come impartiality and universality. Clarity and penetration deepen the nurturing and preservation of the heart. Impartiality and universality refine one's observation and discernment.

    The ancient sages and worthies, though they reached this state through their nature itself, nevertheless achieved it through clarifying their hearts. Such is the essential method of clarification—it depends ultimately upon the individual.

    Minister Kang, despite his lack of formal learning, has taken the clarification of heart as his guiding principle. This is truly worthy of praise. Therefore, I write this discourse to encourage him.
  footnotes:
    - This work is written in the form of a dialogue, a common pedagogical style in Neo-Confucian writings.
    - The reference to Mencius (孟子) draws from Mencius Book 7A, Part 2, on the cultivation of the heart.
    - The progression from the absence of desire to clarity and universal impartiality reflects core Neo-Confucian metaphysical thought about the nature of mind and virtue.
